      <fileDesc>
         <titleStmt>
            <title>Encoding Schema for Television Scripts</title>
            <author>
               <name>Eva Riviere</name>
            </author>
         </titleStmt>
         <publicationStmt>
            <p>Published for the TEI-XML final assignment at the École nationale des chartes.</p>
         </publicationStmt>
         <notesStmt>
            <note type="project_objectives">
               <p>This project tests the adaptability of an XML/TEI-based model to various
                  television script formats, ranging from published editions to professional
                  shooting scripts.</p>
               <list>
                  <item>Digital Structuring: Encoding multimodal narrative elements (dialogue,
                     actions, emotions) within a consistent XML framework.</item>
                  <item>Scholarly Modeling: Using TEI principles to represent both spoken and visual
                     dimensions of performance texts.</item>
                  <item>Interpretive Focus: Highlighting interactions between text, performance, and
                     direction, especially in Fleabag.</item>
               </list>
            </note>
            <note type="custom_rules">
               <p>This ODD implements three specific rules to standardize the encoding of television
                  scripts and ensure data consistency across the corpus:</p>
               <list>
                  <item>Technical Categorization (Attribute Constraint): The <att>type</att>
                     attribute on the <gi>tech</gi> element is restricted to a closed list of values
                     (light, sound, prop, block, FX, montage, transition). This expands standard TEI
                     recommendations to capture specific post-production and on-set signals
                     essential for audiovisual performance texts.</item>
                  <item>Speech Structure (Sequence Constraint): Within the <gi>sp</gi> element, a
                        <gi>speaker</gi> is mandatory and must precede any dialogue paragraphs or
                     technical directions . This rule ensures structural integrity by preventing
                     anonymous dialogue and maintaining a clear link between characters and their
                     lines.</item>
                  <item>Vocal Delivery Context (Schematron Constraint): A Schematron rule mandates
                     that any <gi>stage</gi> direction of <att>type</att> delivery (describing vocal
                     inflection or tone) must be placed inside a speech block . This maintains the
                     logical and functional relationship between performance instructions and the
                     spoken text.</item>
               </list>
            </note>
         </notesStmt>
         <sourceDesc>
            <p>ODD generated from the analysis of a single professional script (dwTS.xml) using the
               "oddbyexample.xsl" transformation, and then manually expanded for multiple type of
               distinct editorial and production contexts scripts.</p>
         </sourceDesc>
