      <body>
         <head>Encoding Schema for Television Scripts</head>
         <p>This ODD aims to provide a stable framework for the digital study of television scripts
            from the early twenty-first century, specifically focusing on the evolution of
            structural conventions across different production contexts. The corpus includes a
            published script (Fleabag), an unofficial amateur reconstruction (Grey’s Anatomy), and a
            professional BBC shooting script (Doctor Who), reflecting the diversity of audiovisual
            performance texts.</p>
         <p>We intend to highlight the interaction between textual dialogue and multimodal
            performance elements by encoding technical directions, character emotions, and visual
            staging. By implementing a consistent XML framework for these disparate formats, we seek
            to model the relationship between the written page and the visual dimension of
            performance, allowing for the extraction of data regarding dramatic structure and
            directorial intent across a diverse corpus.</p>

         <p>It includes five essential elements from the header module: <list>
               <item>
                  <gi>teiHeader</gi> from the header module to store required metadata.</item>
               <item>
                  <gi>fileDesc</gi> from the header module to record information about this
                  file.</item>
               <item>
                  <gi>titleStmt</gi> from the header module to record information about the
                  title.</item>
               <item>
                  <gi>publicationStmt</gi> from the header module to detail the digital
                  publication.</item>
               <item>
                  <gi>sourceDesc</gi> from the header module to record script origins.</item>
            </list> It incorporates the entire "core" and "tei" modules, alongside a specialized
            selection from the "drama" module, including <gi>view</gi>, <gi>camera</gi>, and
               <gi>tech</gi>, to model technical directions and directorial intent. Finally, it
            includes elements from the "textstructure" module but excludes numbered divs, preferring
            simple <gi>div</gi>s with <att>type</att> to define script pages. </p>



